3\\t  - pushes notes to repos\\n    24\\t- Fully transparent\\n    25\\t- No SaaS dependency\\n    26\\t\\n    27\\t### AI Barometer SaaS (this plan)\\n    28\\t- Read-only access to repos via GitHub App\\n    29\\t- Centralised analysis\\n    30\\t- Web-based UI\\n    31\\t- Commercial product\\n    32\\t\\n    33\\t**Key trust principle:**\\n    34\\t> AI Barometer never has access to anything that users didn’t already commit to their own repos.\\n    35\\t\\n    36\\t---\\n    37\\t\\n    38\\t## 2. Target customer & rollout model\\n    39\\t\\n    40\\t### Primary customer (v1)\\n    41\\t- **Org-wide buyer**: CTO / VP Engineering\\n    42\\t- Sales-led, invite-only pilots\\n    43\\t- Known design partners (incl. investors)\\n    44\\t\\n    45\\t### Pricing posture (v1)\\n    46\\t- Org-level pricing\\n    47\\t- Unit = **active AI contributors**\\n    48\\t  - developers whose repos produce AI Barometer notes in a period\\n    49\\t- No self-serve billing in v1\\n    50\\t- Manual provisioning, invoicing\\n    51\\t\\n    52\\t---\\n    53\\t\\n    54\\t## 3. Authentication & access\\n    55\\t\\n    56\\t### Git provider\\n    57\\t- **GitHub only (v1)**\\n    58\\t\\n    59\\t### Integration model\\n    60\\t- **GitHub App**\\n    61\\t  - org-installed\\n    62\\t  - read-only permissions\\n    63\\t  - scoped to selected repos\\n    64\\t\\n    65\\t### Permissions required\\n    66\\t- Read commits & commit metadata\\n    67\\t- Read git notes (`refs/notes/ai-sessions`)\\n    68\\t- Read org + team membership (for aggregation)\\n    69\\t\\n    70\\tNo write permissions. No webhooks required for v1.\\n    71\\t\\n    72\\t---\\n    73\\t\\n    74\\t## 4. Data ingested from repos (minimal, explicit)\\n    75\\t\\n    76\\t### Ingested\\n    77\\t- Git notes under `refs/notes/ai-sessions`\\n    78\\t- Commit metadata only:\\n    79\\t  - commit hash\\n    80\\t  - author (GitHub ID primary, email fallback)\\n    81\\t  - timestamp\\n    82\\t  - branch\\n    83\\t  - repo\\n    84\\t  - basic diff stats (files changed, lines added/removed)\\n    85\\t\\n    86\\t### Explicitly NOT ingested (v1)\\n    87\\t- File contents\\n    88\\t- Full diffs\\n    89\\t- Code semantics beyond stats\\n    90\\t\\n    91\\tThis keeps privacy posture strong and defensible.\\n    92\\t\\n    93\\t---\\n    94\\t\\n    95\\t## 5. Identity & attribution model\\n    96\\t\\n    97\\t### Default identity resolution (v1)\\n    98\\t1. GitHub user ID\\n    99\\t2. Commit author email (fallback)\\n   100\\t\\n   101\\t### Team mapping\\n   102\\t- GitHub org\\n   103\\t- GitHub teams (if present)\\n   104\\t- Users without teams → “Unassigned”\\n   105\\t\\n   106\\tNo custom org-chart UI in v1.\\n   107\\t\\n   108\\tAmbiguous attribution is surfaced as ambiguous, not guessed.\\n   109\\t\\n   110\\t---\\n   111\\t\\n   112\\t## 6. Ingestion & analysis cadence\\n   113\\t\\n   114\\t### Analysis model\\n   115\\t- **Server-side, centralised**\\n   116\\t- **Batch-oriented**\\n   117\\t- Not real-time\\n   118\\t\\n   119\\t### Cadence (flexible, v1 default)\\n   120\\t- Initial full analysis on onboarding\\n   121\\t- Periodic background re-analysis (e.g. daily)\\n   122\\t- Manual “re-run analysis” button for admins\\n   123\\t\\n   124\\t### UX requirement\\n   125\\tUI must clearly show:\\n   126\\t- what data is fully analysed\\n   127\\t- what is pending\\n   128\\t- timestamps of last successful run\\n   129\\t- progress for long-running analysis\\n   130\\t\\n   131\\tFreshness is an implementation detail; **clarity is mandatory**.\\n   132\\t\\n   133\\t---\\n   134\\t\\n   135\\t## 7. Data retention & privacy\\n   136\\t\\n   137\\t### Persisted long-term\\n   138\\t- Derived metrics & summaries\\n   139\\t- Aggregations by org / team / developer / time window\\n   140\\t- Analysis metadata:\\n   141\\t  - schema version\\n   142\\t  - model version\\n   143\\t  - run timestamps\\n   144\\t- Indexes mapping commit → analysed yes/no\\n   145\\t\\n   146\\t### NOT persisted\\n   147\\t- Raw AI session transcripts\\n   148\\t- Raw git notes contents\\n   149\\t- Prompts or AI responses\\n   150\\t\\n   151\\tRepos remain the **source of truth**.  \\n   152\\tRe-analysis re-fetches raw data as needed.\\n   153\\t\\n   154\\t---\\n   155\\t\\n   156\\t## 8. Analysis pipeline (conceptual)\\n   157\\t\\n   158\\t### Input\\n   159\\t- Git notes (AI session transcripts)\\n   160\\t- Commit metadata\\n   161\\t\\n   162\\t### Output (derived data)\\n   163\\tPer AI-assisted commit:\\n   164\\t- session duration\\n   165\\t- iteration count\\n   166\\t- human intervention markers\\n   167\\t- workflow classification (e.g. debug, refactor, migration)\\n   168\\t- friction indicators\\n   169\\t- resolution type (AI-complete vs manual finish)\\n   170\\t\\n   171\\t### Aggregations\\n   172\\t- Per developer\\n   173\\t- Per team\\n   174\\t- Per repo\\n   175\\t- Per org\\n   176\\t- Over time (trend analysis)\\n   177\\t\\n   178\\t### Models\\n   179\\t- Expect to run **local / self-hosted models** for:\\n   180\\t  - summarisation\\n   181\\t  - classification\\n   182\\t- Infra must support batch inference workloads\\n   183\\t\\n   184\\t---\\n   185\\t\\n   186\\t## 9. UI structure (v1)\\n   187\\t\\n   188\\t### Landing dashboard (CTO / exec)\\n   189\\tSingle calm overview answering:\\n   190\\t1. Is AI being used?\\n   191\\t2. Where is it helping vs struggling?\\n   192\\t3. Is this improving over time?\\n   193\\t\\n   194\\tContents:\\n   195\\t- % of commits AI-assisted (trend)\\n   196\\t- Median session duration & iteration trends\\n   197\\t- Top friction workflow categories\\n   198\\t- One or two “positive leverage” insights\\n   199\\t\\n   200\\tNo rankings. No shaming. No scores.\\n   201\\t\\n   202\\t---\\n   203\\t\\n   204\\t### Drill-down model (explicitly allowed)\\n   205\\t\\n   206\\tAccess mirrors Git access; no artificial restrictions.\\n   207\\t\\n   208\\t- Org → team → individual → session summaries → **raw transcripts**\\n   209\\t- Raw transcripts = git notes content\\n   210\\t- Transcripts hidden by default, explicitly expanded\\n   211\\t\\n   212\\tGuardrails are **UX-based**, not permission-based.\\n   213\\t\\n   214\\t---\\n   215\\t\\n   216\\t### Individual developer view\\n   217\\t- Personal reflective dashboard\\n   218\\t- Trends over time\\n   219\\t- Common workflows\\n   220\\t- Friction patterns\\n   221\\t- No peer ranking by default (v1)\\n   222\\t\\n   223\\tDesigned as a **mirror**, not an evaluation.\\n   224\\t\\n   225\\t---\\n   226\\t\\n   227\\t## 10. Non-goals (v1)\\n   228\\t\\n   229\\tDo NOT implement yet:\\n   230\\t- Billing automation\\n   231\\t- Self-serve onboarding\\n   232\\t- Real-time analysis\\n   233\\t- Cross-org benchmarking\\n   234\\t- Leaderboards (expected later)\\n   235\\t- Custom team builders\\n   236\\t- HR system integrations\\n   237\\t- Code content analysis\\n   238\\t\\n   239\\t---\\n   240\\t\\n   241\\t## 11. Infra & deployment assumptions\\n   242\\t\\n   243\\t### Backend\\n   244\\t- Web API (auth, orchestration)\\n   245\\t- Job queue for ingestion & analysis\\n   246\\t- Worker fleet for batch analysis (CPU + optional GPU)\\n   247\\t- Object storage for intermediate artifacts\\n   248\\t- Relational DB for derived metrics\\n   249\\t\\n   250\\t### Frontend\\n   251\\t- Web app (CTO / manager / dev views)\\n   252\\t- Read-only dashboards\\n   253\\t- Clear analysis state indicators\\n   254\\t\\n   255\\t### Scale expectations (v1)\\n   256\\t- Tens of orgs\\n   257\\t- Hundreds of repos\\n   258\\t- Thousands of active AI sessions per day\\n   259\\t- Batch processing acceptable\\n   260\\t\\n   261\\t---\\n   262\\t\\n   263\\t## 12. Milestones (suggested)\\n   264\\t\\n   265\\t### Phase 1\\n   266\\t- GitHub App\\n   267\\t- Repo ingestion\\n   268\\t- Notes fetching\\n   269\\t- Minimal derived metrics\\n   270\\t- CLI / internal API verification\\n   271\\t\\n   272\\t### Phase 2\\n   273\\t- Analysis pipeline v1\\n   274\\t- Local model integration\\n   275\\t- Derived schema stabilisation\\n   276\\t\\n   277\\t### Phase 3\\n   278\\t- Web UI v1\\n   279\\t- CTO landing dashboard\\n   280\\t- Drill-down views\\n   281\\t\\n   282\\t### Phase 4\\n   283\\t- Pilot onboarding\\n   284\\t- Feedback loops\\n   285\\t- Metric refinement\\n   286\\t\\n   287\\t---\\n   288\\t\\n   289\\t## 13. Product invariants (do not break)\\n   290\\t\\n   291\\t- No history mutation\\n   292\\t- No hidden data capture\\n   293\\t- No surprise visibility expansion\\n   294\\t- Analysis explains itself\\n   295\\t- Trust > cleverness\\n   296\\t\\n   297\\t---\\n   298\\t\\n   299\\t## Summary\\n   300\\t\\n   301\\tAI Barometer SaaS is a **sense-making layer** over AI-assisted development, not a monitoring tool.\\n   302\\t\\n   303\\tThe capture layer is open and transparent.  \\n   304\\tThe SaaS layer is optional, analytical, and designed to help humans improve how they work with AI — individually and collectively.\\n   305\\t\\n   306\\tBuild for clarity, not control.\\n\"}}\n{\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-10T01:53:59.751Z\",\"type\":\"turn_context\",\"payload\":{\"cwd\":\"/Users/daveslutzkin/dev/ai-barometer\",\"approval_policy\":\"on-request\",\"sandbox_policy\":{\"type\":\"workspace-write\",\"network_access\":false,\"exclude_tmpdir_env_var\":false,\"exclude_slash_tmp\":false},\"model\":\"gpt-5.3-codex\",\"personality\":\"pragmatic\",\"collaboration_mode\":{\"mode\":\"default\",\"settings\":{\"model\":\"gpt-5.3-codex\",\"reasoning_effort\":\"xhigh\",\"developer_instructions\":\"# Collaboration Mode: Default\\n\\nYou are now in Default mode. Any previous instructions for other modes (e.g. Plan mode) are no longer active.\\n\\nYour active mode changes only when new developer instructions with a different `<collaboration_mode>...</collaboration_mode>` change it; user requests or tool descriptions do not change mode by themselves. Kno